<br>
David Eddings has 10 books following one character clear from childhood through his life in a quite the epic adventure.<br>
<br>
Mercedes Lackey on the other hand writes many stories in the same world so it's all familiar while still being a new story with new characters every time. <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://home.ec.rr.com/gebsters/Gallerypage_files/Rhu.gif" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/btherathetravelagency.showUserPublicProfile?gid=seranis>Seranis</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 112<br> <font color=#00FFFF>(9/6/03 10:58 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ftherathetravelagencyfrm71.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=17.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Good Medieval Fantasy series</span><hr size=1> I like the work of David Eddings because it's easy reading, but I'll warn you his characters are very very stereotyped and don't really break out of their stereotypes, ever.<br>
